Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England"},"en":{"1357–1402":"1357–1402","1353–1420":"1353–1420","1385–1450":"1385–1450","1325–1400":"1325–1400","1335–1422":"1335–1422","1402":"1402","1325":"1325","1357":"1357","1335":"1335","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1420":"1420","1353":"1353","1385":"1385","1450":"1450","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dorre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Haitian (<b>Dorcé</b>):","probably an ornamental name, with the first element based on French <i>d'or</i> ‘of gold’. Compare   Dorcely  .","alternatively, perhaps a habitational name from a place in Haiti called Dorcé."],"variants":[{"name":"Dorcely","meanings":["Haitian (also <b>Dorcély</b>): probably an ornamental name, a variant of <b>Dorcé</b> (see   Dorce  )."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":25,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Eleanor Dorre was born in 1357, in Buckinghamshire, England, her father, Thomas Dorre, was 32 and her mother, Lady Thomas Dorre, was 22. She married Geoffrey Dormer II in 1383, in Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1402, in her hometown, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1357–1402":"1357–1402","1353–1420":"1353–1420","1385–1450":"1385–1450","1325–1400":"1325–1400","1335–1422":"1335–1422","1402":"1402","1325":"1325","1357":"1357","1335":"1335","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1420":"1420","1353":"1353","1385":"1385","1450":"1450","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"1357–1402":"1357–1402","1353–1420":"1353–1420","1385–1450":"1385–1450","1325–1400":"1325–1400","1335–1422":"1335–1422","1402":"1402","1325":"1325","1357":"1357","1335":"1335","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1420":"1420","1353":"1353","1385":"1385","1450":"1450","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamsh